---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import ToolReview from '../../components/ToolReview.astro';
import { siteFromHost } from '../../content';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';

const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '/alternatives/sendlane-alternative';
const title = 'Best Sendlane Alternatives for Shopify (2026)';
const desc = 'Why Shopify merchants leave Sendlane — package pricing at scale, self-serve appetite, overlap with cheaper stacks — plus eight ranked alternatives and migration checklist.';

const altSlugs = ['sequenzy', 'klaviyo', 'omnisend', 'drip', 'rejoiner', 'postscript', 'activecampaign', 'brevo'];
const alternatives = altSlugs.map((s) => appBySlug(s)!);

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Why do Shopify stores leave Sendlane?',
    answer: 'Sendlane delivers guided retention well — until package pricing exceeds ROI at current order volume, or teams mature enough to want self-serve speed without onboarding calls. Some leave because Sendlane\'s ecommerce depth overlaps cheaper tools after migration stabilized their flows. Others need predictive analytics Sendlane trails Klaviyo on, or pay-per-email economics Sequenzy offers.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is leaving Sendlane a downgrade?',
    answer: 'Not necessarily. Sendlane fits brands investing in white-glove retention. Leaving for Sequenzy or Omnisend often trades guided support for faster iteration and lower cost — acceptable when your team now owns lifecycle ops confidently. Leaving for Brevo alone may be downgrade if you still need Sendlane-level automation depth.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How long does Sendlane migration take?',
    answer: 'Plan 2–4 weeks. Sendlane\'s organized templates migrate cleaner than Klaviyo chaos — document live flows, rebuild welcome and cart first, run 14-day suppression, then post-purchase and winback. Sendlane support sometimes assists exit migrations professionally; ask during contract renewal negotiations.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I export Sendlane automations?',
    answer: 'Export flow documentation and contact lists with consent metadata. Automations rebuild manually in the new platform — use Sendlane\'s clarity as spec to simplify, not clone every branch. Many migrants delete edge-case flows Sendlane onboarding helped create but nobody maintains.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Best Sendlane alternative for SMS?',
    answer: 'Postscript for SMS-first DTC with dedicated compliance tooling. Omnisend for bundled email, SMS, and push. Klaviyo SMS if consolidating into profile-based stack. Do not dual-run Sendlane SMS during overlap.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Sequenzy vs Sendlane after migration?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy suits teams leaving Sendlane because guided setup completed and ongoing pay-per-email economics beat package renewals. Sendlane suits teams still needing migration support and deliverability consultation — if that describes you, reconsider leaving.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What happens to Sendlane segments on exit?',
    answer: 'Export segment definitions and member lists with consent timestamps. Rebuild dynamic segments via Shopify sync in the new platform. Sendlane static lists decay quickly — prioritize behavioral segments over imported CSVs.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I negotiate Sendlane renewal instead of switching?',
    answer: 'Renegotiation works when the pain is price, not fit — annual commits sometimes drop 15–25%. Switch when you need different billing models, faster self-serve iteration, or Klaviyo-level predictive depth Sendlane does not prioritize.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should I stay on Sendlane?',
    answer: 'Stay if onboarding value remains high, attributed email revenue justifies package cost, and your team prefers support calls over self-serve builders. Sendlane still excels for mid-market DTC without in-house retention specialists.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/alternatives">Alternatives</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Sendlane alternatives</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Post-onboarding reality</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Best Sendlane alternatives for Shopify</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          Sendlane earns loyalty during migration — someone finally rebuilt your cart flow correctly. The reconsideration arrives at renewal: package pricing that made sense at 800 orders/month feels heavy at 2,400, or your team now maintains flows confidently and paying for guided retention feels like insurance you stopped filing claims on. Leaving Sendlane is rarely anger. It is arithmetic plus maturity.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[#5d3a1d]">
          We ranked eight alternatives for Shopify merchants exiting Sendlane — not generic swaps. Sequenzy leads when pay-per-email and agent-first iteration beat package renewals. Klaviyo leads when predictive analytics was always the gap. See <a class="link" href="/compare/sendlane-vs-klaviyo">Sendlane vs Klaviyo</a> and <a class="link" href="/compare/rejoiner-vs-sendlane">Rejoiner vs Sendlane</a> for adjacent decisions.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          title="Top Sendlane replacements for Shopify"
          picks={[
            { label: 'Best overall alternative', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Agent-first lifecycle playbooks with pay-per-email economics when Sendlane package renewals exceed value post-onboarding.' },
            { label: 'Best analytics upgrade', tool: 'Klaviyo', reason: 'Predictive CLV and Shopify maximums when Sendlane depth was sufficient but data ceiling was not.' },
            { label: 'Best self-serve multichannel', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Prebuilt journeys with SMS and push without package pricing or onboarding scheduling.' },
            { label: 'Best workflow control', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Visual builder for operators who outgrew Sendlane templates but want hands-on automation design.' },
            { label: 'Best recovery specialist', tool: 'Rejoiner', reason: 'Cart-focused stack when Sendlane felt broad but recovery attribution was your only KPI.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>Why Shopify merchants leave Sendlane</h2>
        <p>
          Package pricing at scale is the renewal-table conversation. A pet brand loved Sendlane onboarding — welcome, cart, post-purchase live in three weeks. Eighteen months later order volume doubled but email attributed revenue per send flatlined, and the custom package quote exceeds what Sequenzy or Omnisend would cost for the same send patterns. Sendlane's value was front-loaded; the bill is recurring.
        </p>
        <p>
          Self-serve appetite grows after onboarding completes. Teams that needed hand-holding in month one maintain flows confidently in month eighteen — yet still schedule support calls for changes they could make in Omnisend in an afternoon. Sendlane optimizes for brands without retention staff; graduates sometimes feel slowed by the same support model that saved them initially.
        </p>
        <p>
          Feature overlap with cheaper stacks triggers pragmatic exits. Once Sendlane stabilized core lifecycle, some merchants realize recovery-only Rejoiner plus Sequenzy strategy layer costs less than Sendlane's full package — or Klaviyo's predictive winback justifies profile pricing Sendlane approximated without matching. Consolidation after tool sprawl also matters: leaving Sendlane email to unify SMS in Postscript while lifecycle moves to Sequenzy.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sendlane is not a platform people rage-quit. If you still lack retention ownership internally and deliverability scares you, renewal negotiation may beat migration. This guide serves stores whose Sendlane investment paid off and whose next chapter needs different economics or predictive depth — not stores still in onboarding panic.
        </p>

        <h2>Sendlane migration checklist for Shopify</h2>
        <p>Sendlane accounts are usually well-organized — migration is documentation-heavy, not archaeology. Run this before cancellation.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Export Sendlane flow inventory.</strong> List every live automation with last enrollment and attributed revenue. Deprioritize low performers Sendlane onboarding created defensively.</li>
          <li><strong>Export consent and contacts.</strong> CSV with email, SMS consent, timestamps, and source. TCPA records for SMS migration.</li>
          <li><strong>Document suppression rules.</strong> Sendlane's strength — capture purchase suppression, recent buyer rules, VIP exclusions. Rebuild explicitly in new platform.</li>
          <li><strong>Map Shopify integrations.</strong> Reviews, loyalty, subscription apps feeding Sendlane segments — reconnect in new stack.</li>
          <li><strong>Install new platform and sync Shopify.</strong> Verify catalog, orders, and browse events before contact import.</li>
          <li><strong>Rebuild welcome and cart first.</strong> Sendlane migrants usually know these flows cold — fast to test, highest revenue impact.</li>
          <li><strong>Run parallel suppression 14 days.</strong> Non-negotiable during platform overlap. Sendlane's recovery was reliable — duplicate sends destroy trust fast.</li>
          <li><strong>Migrate post-purchase, winback, replenishment.</strong> Simplify branches Sendlane support added for edge cases you never saw trigger.</li>
          <li><strong>Redirect capture integrations.</strong> Popups and forms must feed new lists — stale Sendlane growth breaks continuity.</li>
          <li><strong>Port SMS carefully.</strong> Cancel Sendlane SMS before activating new SMS platform. One TCPA compliance path during migration.</li>
          <li><strong>Warm domain if ESP changes.</strong> Ramp volume 7–14 days. See <a class="link" href="/use-cases/deliverability">deliverability guide</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep Sendlane read-only 90 days.</strong> Reference during rebuild, then cancel per contract terms.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: CPG brand renewing Sendlane at 3x original quote</h2>
        <p>
          A $320k/mo CPG brand onboarded Sendlane two years ago with guided migration — flows worked, deliverability was clean, SMS coordinated with email. Renewal quote jumped from $420/mo to $1,180/mo at 48,000 contacts. Finance asked whether Klaviyo predictive winback or Sequenzy pay-per-email justified switch. Sendlane flows were healthy; pricing was the trigger. They migrated to Sequenzy in four weeks — Sendlane suppression logic documented well, rebuild was straightforward. Bill dropped to $210/mo at actual send volume. Attributed revenue within 3% of Sendlane baseline month two; winback refresh added $2,800/mo incremental by month three.
        </p>

        <h2>90-day rollout: Sendlane exit with documentation advantage</h2>
        <p>
          Days 1–14: Export Sendlane flow inventory with revenue attribution — Sendlane accounts are usually organized. Negotiate renewal once with documented competitive quotes before committing to migration. Export consent including SMS TCPA records.
        </p>
        <p>
          Days 15–30: Connect new platform. Sendlane migrants rebuild welcome and cart quickly because suppression rules were already documented. Parallel suppression fourteen days — non-negotiable given Sendlane recovery reliability customers expect.
        </p>
        <p>
          Days 31–60: Post-purchase, winback, replenishment. Simplify edge-case branches Sendlane support added that never triggered. Port SMS with compliance handoff if leaving Sendlane SMS.
        </p>
        <p>
          Days 61–90: Cancel per contract terms after archive period. Compare deliverability, attributed revenue, and ops hours against Sendlane baseline. Keep Sendlane read-only ninety days for reference.
        </p>

        <h2>Margin math: Sendlane renewal shock versus migration</h2>
        <p>
          Sendlane renewal at $1,180/mo versus Sequenzy at $210/mo saves $970/mo — $11,640/year. Migration agency at $8k pays back in eight months on fees alone. Klaviyo at $650/mo saves less ($530/mo) but adds predictive winback — model incremental revenue not just fee delta. Sendlane's value was guided onboarding; that value is sunk cost — do not pay renewal premium for historical hand-holding.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hidden Sendlane value: deliverability consultation and suppression discipline. New platform must replicate suppression explicitly — do not assume defaults match Sendlane configuration.
        </p>

        <h2>Failure rehearsal: leaving Sendlane prematurely</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Migration before renewal negotiation.</strong> Sendlane matches competitor quote if asked — switching costs avoided. Fix: negotiate once with documented alternatives.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Suppression logic lost.</strong> Sendlane had tight purchase suppression; new platform defaults are looser. Fix: document Sendlane rules as rebuild spec.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>SMS port gap.</strong> Sendlane SMS cancelled before Postscript port completes. Fix: schedule SMS migration separately with compliance lead time.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Edge case branch removal.</strong> Team deletes Sendlane branches that actually handled subscription edge cases. Fix: review enrollment logs before deleting branches.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Leave during onboarding.</strong> Store still in Sendlane setup panic switches — loses guided support before flows stable. Fix: complete onboarding or negotiate exit assistance.
        </p>

        <h2>When Sendlane renewal makes sense</h2>
        <p>
          Stay when renewal pricing is competitive, flows are healthy, team lacks migration bandwidth, and deliverability record is strong. Leave when renewal quote exceeds 2x original without feature addition, or when predictive depth justifies Klaviyo investment. See <a class="link" href="/compare/rejoiner-vs-sendlane">Rejoiner vs Sendlane</a> for recovery-focused comparison.
        </p>
      
        <h2>Integration dependency audit before Sendlane disconnect</h2>
        <p>Platform exits fail operationally when connected apps keep pushing data into a system you partially deactivated. Before disconnecting Sendlane from Shopify, inventory every integration: subscription tools, loyalty apps, review platforms, helpdesk systems, popup capture tools, and SMS coordination partners. For each integration document data direction, events triggered, segments or tags modified, and business criticality. Critical integrations must reconnect on the replacement platform before core automations go live. Low-value integrations from deprecated apps should sunset rather than migrate — most merchants accumulate integration debt that amplifies migration risk beyond the core guided retention transition itself.</p>
        <p>Capture tools feeding Sendlane list IDs require theme and checkout audit. Grep storefront theme files, checkout extensions, and post-purchase pages for hardcoded list identifiers or webhook URLs pointing at Sendlane. SMS coordination with email recovery needs documented suppression owner per trigger type — email platform and SMS platform optimizing independently creates customer complaints within days of overlap. Export UTM and campaign naming conventions if analytics dashboards depend on Sendlane campaign structure; attribution reporting resets during migration quarter unless naming discipline transfers deliberately.</p>
        <h2>Quarterly optimization after leaving Sendlane</h2>
        <p>First thirty days post-migration focus on suppression integrity and deliverability stability. Days thirty through ninety focus on revenue optimization by flow type. Archive Sendlane baseline metrics during migration — attributed revenue by automation, send volume, complaint rate, recovery timing — and compare weekly against new platform performance. Cart recovery should reach parity within two weeks; winback and replenishment should exceed old platform performance if migration rationale was capability upgrade rather than pure cost reduction. Underperformance triggers suppression audit before creative audit — overly aggressive recent-buyer exclusions silently prevent enrollment more often than weak subject lines.</p>
        <p>Segment hygiene at day sixty prevents repeating billing or deliverability problems under new platform model. Sunset unengaged contacts regardless of how new platform bills — per-contact, per-send, or flat tier. Quarterly review documents which automations required manual intervention versus ran untouched; increasing untouched percentage indicates playbook stabilization. Deliverability seed tests at day thirty and ninety on Gmail and Outlook catch reputation issues before they compound across peak promotional calendar.</p>
        <h2>Building the business case and choosing replacement timing</h2>
        <p>Finance approves migration with conservative revenue projections, not feature checklists. Present twelve-month cost of staying on Sendlane including platform fees, operator labor, agency support, and opportunity cost of flows the current platform cannot run. Present migration cost: labor, agency rebuild, deliverability ramp risk, and three-month conservative incremental revenue projection from flows enabled on replacement platform. Break-even month calculation determines urgency — fee-only savings with twelve-month payback rarely justify migration; revenue lift with four-month payback usually does. Negotiate with Sendlane once before migrating if contract renewal is near; documented competitive quotes sometimes reduce renewal cost enough to fund hybrid improvement without full exit.</p>
        <p>Replacement timing should avoid peak revenue weeks — post-BFCM January, post-Valentine March lull, mid-summer for seasonal categories. Never port SMS numbers during highest promotional month. Never run parallel cart recovery through busy sale weekend without named kill-switch owner available in real time. Migration is operational project with revenue risk; schedule it deliberately rather than reacting to invoice frustration with rushed cutover that costs more in duplicate sends and deliverability damage than platform fees ever did.</p>
  
        <h2>Operator playbook: who owns what after migration</h2>
        <p>Every migration succeeds technically and fails organizationally when ownership is unclear. Assign named owner for: welcome and post-purchase copy edits, cart recovery timing and discount escalation rules, winback and replenishment calendar, popup and capture integration health, SMS compliance and opt-out monitoring, deliverability and complaint rate review, and platform billing audit. One person can own multiple roles on small teams but names must exist in writing — not "marketing" as abstract entity. During first ninety days post-migration, owner sends weekly three-line status to leadership: attributed revenue versus baseline, any duplicate-send incidents, and planned flow changes next week. This rhythm catches drift before it becomes quarterly surprise.</p>
        <p>Agency relationships need explicit scope reset after migration. If agency maintained previous platform flows, clarify whether agency rebuilds on new platform, trains internal owner, or exits automation scope entirely. Hybrid agency-internal ownership fails when both assume the other edits suppression rules before sale week. Document which flows agency may touch without approval versus which require internal sign-off — typically cart discount escalation and winback offer depth are internal decisions while template formatting is agency-appropriate. Contractor access should expire automatically ninety days post-migration unless renewed deliberately.</p>
        <h2>Deliverability and compliance continuity</h2>
        <p>Platform migration is deliverability event even when sending domain unchanged. New ESP routes mail through different infrastructure with different reputation pools. Ramp plan: days one through seven send only to engaged forty-five-day openers at fifty percent of normal campaign volume; days eight through fourteen expand to ninety-day engaged at seventy-five percent volume; day fifteen onward resume normal segmentation if complaint rate stays below threshold. Cart and transactional automations can run at full volume earlier if enrolled segments are purely behavioral purchase triggers rather than bulk marketing lists — but monitor complaint rate daily regardless.</p>
        <p>Compliance continuity for SMS migrations requires legal review of exported consent records before first send on new platform. Document opt-in source, timestamp, and keyword for every SMS subscriber. Exclude records with ambiguous consent rather than risk TCPA exposure — losing ten percent of list is cheaper than single class-action exposure. Email marketing consent similarly requires documented source; GDPR and CAN-SPAM both care about provable opt-in even when platforms technically allow import. Archive consent export files seven years minimum. Unsubscribe and preference center links must work before any broadcast — test on mobile devices where eighty percent of Shopify customers read email.</p>
        <h2>Revenue attribution reset and reporting discipline</h2>
        <p>Accept attribution reset during migration quarter — comparing new platform attributed revenue against old platform last-quarter numbers is directionally useful but not pixel-perfect. UTM schemas, attribution windows, and click-definition differ across platforms. Build new baseline from week six onward rather than demanding week two matches old platform peak. Track flow-level revenue weekly: welcome, cart, browse, post-purchase, winback, replenishment, campaigns — each should trend independently. If total attributed revenue rises but cart recovery falls, investigate suppression collision before celebrating aggregate number.</p>
        <p>Finance reporting should separate platform cost as percentage of attributed email revenue monthly — target under three percent for mature DTC, under five percent during growth phase, investigate above seven percent regardless of platform choice. Include operator labor hours in total cost of ownership calculation quarterly. Platform that saves two hundred dollars monthly but adds eight hours maintenance is more expensive than platform costing two hundred more monthly with two hours maintenance. Migration business case validation happens at day ninety with real numbers, not projected numbers from sales demos — update internal ROI model with actuals and decide whether to deepen investment in chosen platform or plan next transition if goals missed.</p>
</article>

      <section class="container space-y-12 py-16">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Ranked alternatives</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Eight Sendlane alternatives for Shopify stores</h2>

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[0]}
          rank={1}
          badge="Top pick"
          paragraphs={[
            'Sequenzy is the Sendlane alternative we recommend when onboarding succeeded and package renewals became the pain. Sendlane taught you what good lifecycle looks like — Sequenzy lets your team iterate without renewal calls. Agent-first playbooks express winback, replenishment, and VIP suppression in plain language; pay-per-email pricing aligns cost with sends rather than Sendlane package tiers.',
            'You lose white-glove deliverability consultation — gain speed and economics. For teams Sendlane trained to think in lifecycle terms, Sequenzy is the natural graduation platform, not a downgrade.',
            'Pair with Postscript for SMS if Sendlane SMS was active. Compare <a class="link" href="/compare/drip-vs-sendlane">Drip vs Sendlane</a> if workflow drawing appeals more than agent-first setup.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[1]}
          rank={2}
          paragraphs={[
            'Klaviyo is the Sendlane upgrade when predictive analytics was always the missing layer — CLV-based winback, collection browse, variant back-in-stock. Sendlane migrants often have clean suppression habits that translate well to Klaviyo hygiene.',
            'Profile pricing may exceed Sendlane packages at some list sizes — model before switching. Choose Klaviyo when data depth drives margin, not when Sendlane economics were fine and you merely wanted self-serve.',
            'See <a class="link" href="/compare/sendlane-vs-klaviyo">Sendlane vs Klaviyo</a> for full tradeoff map.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[2]}
          rank={3}
          paragraphs={[
            'Omnisend replaces Sendlane for self-serve multichannel speed — prebuilt cart, welcome, post-purchase with email, SMS, and push. No package quotes, no onboarding scheduling. Sendlane migrants maintain flows themselves within days.',
            'Less consultative than Sendlane, sufficient for SMB DTC catalogs Sendlane already proved manageable. Credible permanent home, not temporary bridge.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[3]}
          rank={4}
          paragraphs={[
            'Drip appeals to Sendlane graduates who want visual workflow control without package pricing. Branching by collection and discount sensitivity with clearer builder UX than rebuilding in Klaviyo.',
            'Per-contact pricing applies — model against Sendlane renewal quote. Pick Drip when someone enjoys drawing automation maps weekly.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[4]}
          rank={5}
          paragraphs={[
            'Rejoiner is the narrow alternative when Sendlane felt broad but cart recovery was your only measurable win — recovery specialist with Shopify-native focus. Pair with Sequenzy for full lifecycle strategy outside recovery.',
            'Compare <a class="link" href="/compare/rejoiner-vs-sendlane">Rejoiner vs Sendlane</a> if recovery attribution dominated your Sendlane ROI story.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[5]}
          rank={6}
          paragraphs={[
            'Postscript when leaving Sendlane to consolidate SMS-first with best-in-class compliance — email moves to Sequenzy or Klaviyo separately. Common stack split after Sendlane bundled SMS underperformed dedicated tools.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[6]}
          rank={7}
          paragraphs={[
            'ActiveCampaign when Sendlane lifecycle overlapped sales CRM needs — wholesale pipelines, rep-assigned follow-up. More CRM, less pure DTC focus than Sendlane\'s ecommerce templates.',
          ]}
        />

        <ToolReview
          app={alternatives[7]}
          rank={8}
          paragraphs={[
            'Brevo is the cost-down exit when Sendlane package exceeded value and automation needs simplified post-audit — many Sendlane flows were overbuilt. Pay-per-email without Sendlane onboarding premium.',
            'Accept lighter Shopify segmentation — or choose Sequenzy if strategy guidance mattered as much as Sendlane onboarding did.',
          ]}
        />
      </section>

      <div class="container mb-12 max-w-4xl card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Pricing comparison vs Sendlane</h2>
        <p class="px-5 pb-4 text-[#5d3a1d]">Sendlane uses custom packages — illustrative comparisons for mid-market DTC.</p>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Platform</th><th>~10k contacts</th><th>~25k contacts</th><th>~50k contacts</th><th>Billing model</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Sendlane (leaving)</td><td>$83–200</td><td>Custom</td><td>Custom</td><td>Package pricing</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sequenzy</td><td>$19–79</td><td>$49–149</td><td>$99–249</td><td>Pay per email sent</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Klaviyo</td><td>$150–200</td><td>$350–450</td><td>$600–900+</td><td>Active profiles + SMS</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Omnisend</td><td>$60–100</td><td>$120–180</td><td>$200–350</td><td>Contacts + volume</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Drip</td><td>$80–120</td><td>$150–250</td><td>$280–450</td><td>People in account</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Brevo</td><td>$25–65</td><td>$50–120</td><td>$100–200</td><td>Email volume</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="container max-w-4xl pb-8 text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related guides</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/apps/sendlane">Sendlane review</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sendlane-vs-klaviyo">Sendlane vs Klaviyo</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/rejoiner-vs-sendlane">Rejoiner vs Sendlane</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/postscript-vs-sendlane">Postscript vs Sendlane</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/alternatives">All alternatives</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Sendlane alternatives FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
